The '''Haiti national football team''' ({{langx|fr|Équipe d'Haïti de football}}, {{langx|ht|Ekip Foutbòl Ayiti}}) represents [[Haiti]] in men's international [[Association football|football]], which is governed by the [[Haitian Football Federation|Fédération Haïtienne de Football]] ({{langx|en|Haitian Football Federation}}, {{langx|ht|Federasyon Foutbòl Ayisyen}}), the governing body for [[football in Haiti]] founded in 1904. It has been an affiliate member of [[FIFA]] since 1934 and a founding affiliate member of [[CONCACAF]] since 1961. Regionally, it is an affiliate member of [[Caribbean Football Union|CFU]] in the Caribbean Zone. From 1938 to 1961, it was a member of [[Confederación Centroamericana y del Caribe de Fútbol|CCCF]], the former governing body of football in Central America and Caribbean and a predecessor confederation of CONCACAF, and also a member of [[Panamerican Championship#Panamerican Football Confederation|PFC]], the former unified confederation of the Americas.

Haiti has qualified for the [[FIFA World Cup]] twice ([[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]] and [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026]]) and is the only Caribbean nation to have done so.

Haiti has participated seventeen times in CONCACAF's premier continental competition, it is the only Caribbean team to have won a title, winning the [[CONCACAF Championship]] in [[1973 CONCACAF Championship|1973]]. The team's best performance under the [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]] format was reaching the semifinals in [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2019]]. It has participated twice in League A and twice in League B of the [[CONCACAF Nations League]]. It has also participated once in the [[Copa América]], which was the 100th anniversary edition in [[Copa América Centenario|2016]]. 

Regionally, the team won the [[CCCF Championship]] in [[1957 CCCF Championship|1957]] (organized by CCCF), the [[CFU Championship]] in [[1979 CFU Championship|1979]] and the [[Caribbean Cup]] in [[2007 Caribbean Cup|2007]] (both organized by CFU).

Haiti's home ground is [[Stade Sylvio Cator]] in [[Port-au-Prince]] and the team's manager is [[Sébastien Migné]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icihaiti.com/en/news-41843-icihaiti-football-sebastien-migne-new-coach-of-the-grenadiers-senior.html|title=Sebastien Migné new coach of the Grenadiers Sénior|website=Icihaiti.com|date=9 March 2024|access-date=22 March 2025}}</ref>
Haiti has one of the longest football traditions in the region, being the second Caribbean team to make the FIFA World Cup, after qualifying from winning the 1973 CONCACAF Championship. They made their World Cup debut in 1974, and were beaten in the group stage by [[Italy national football team|Italy]], [[Poland national football team|Poland]], and [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], who were all pre-tournament favorites. In 2016, Haiti qualified for the 100th anniversary of the Copa América, by defeating [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]].
Haiti qualified for the 2026 FIFA World Cup for the second time in its history, after defeating [[Nicaragua national football team|Nicaragua]] 2–0 in [[Curaçao]], on the final matchday to top Group C of the qualifiers.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cwy70v7grl4o|title=Haiti reach World Cup despite coach having never been to the country|date=19 November 2025|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 November 2025}}</ref>